  "prompt": "What is the difference between '-' and '-=' operators in C++?",
  "response": "In C++, the '-' and '-=' operators are both used for subtraction, but they have slight differences in their usage and behavior:\n\n1. '-' Operator (Subtraction):\n```cpp\nint a = 10;\nint b = 5;\nint result = a - b;  // result is 5\n```\n- Performs subtraction between two operands\n- Returns the result of the subtraction\n- Does not modify the original operands\n\n2. '-=' Operator (Subtraction Assignment):\n```cpp\nint a = 10;\na -= 5;  // equivalent to: a = a - 5\n// Now a is 5\n```\n- Subtracts the right operand from the left operand\n- Modifies the left operand in-place\n- Combines subtraction and assignment in a single operation\n\nHere are more detailed examples:\n\n```cpp\nint main() {\n    // Simple subtraction\n    int x = 10;\n    int y = 5;\n    int z = x - y;  // z is 5, x and y remain unchanged\n\n    // Subtraction assignment\n    int a = 10;\n    a -= 5;  // a becomes 5\n\n    // With different types\n    double d = 10.5;\n    d -= 3.2;  // d becomes 7.3\n\n    // Works with more complex expressions\n    int b = 20;\n    b -= x + y;  // equivalent to: b = b - (x + y)\n\n    return 0;\n}\n```\n\nKey differences:\n1. '-' creates a new result without modifying operands\n2. '-=' modifies the left operand directly\n3. '-=' is often more concise and can be slightly more efficient\n\nPerformance and Usage:\n- '-=' is typically preferred when you want to modify a variable in-place\n- '-' is used when you want to create a new value without changing the original\n\nExample in a loop:\n```cpp\nint total = 100;\nfor (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {\n    total -= i;  // Progressively reduces total\n}\n```\n\nBoth operators work similarly with different types (int, float, double, etc.) and support the same basic subtraction logic.",
